00:00:53,762 --> 00:00:54,721
What?

2
00:00:56,639 --> 00:00:57,474
Do you know me?

3
00:01:05,815 --> 00:01:07,609
HOW THE PROFILER CAUGHT GU YOUNG-CHUN

4
00:01:07,692 --> 00:01:09,069
<i>Gu Young-chun.</i>

5
00:01:10,028 --> 00:01:11,780
You're the guy who caught him.

6
00:01:17,035 --> 00:01:17,994
So you do know me.

7
00:01:20,663 --> 00:01:23,958
I guess you were very interested
in Gu Young-chun's case.

8
00:01:24,876 --> 00:01:27,128
He took the credit for my killing.

9
00:01:30,465 --> 00:01:32,008
That was a ridiculous lie.

10
00:01:32,842 --> 00:01:33,968
What do you mean?

11
00:01:36,221 --> 00:01:38,723
I'm not here to interrogate you.

12
00:01:40,141 --> 00:01:41,768
I'm here to help you.

13
00:01:43,186 --> 00:01:44,145
You…

14
00:01:45,230 --> 00:01:46,189
want to help me?

15
00:01:49,776 --> 00:01:50,944
But why?

16
00:01:52,153 --> 00:01:53,279
Why would you help me?

17
00:01:53,863 --> 00:01:56,449
My job is to analyze why this happened.

18
00:01:57,909 --> 00:01:59,828
So I'm here to speak with you

19
00:02:00,662 --> 00:02:02,247
and learn more about you.

20
00:02:02,831 --> 00:02:03,748
Speak about what?

21
00:02:03,832 --> 00:02:06,251
Well, anything.

22
00:02:10,463 --> 00:02:11,714
Do you live alone?

23
00:02:13,466 --> 00:02:14,676
Then who do you live with?

24
00:02:14,759 --> 00:02:16,052
My mom and younger brother.

25
00:02:16,136 --> 00:02:17,220
What about your father?

26
00:02:19,180 --> 00:02:20,223
He died.

27
00:02:21,099 --> 00:02:22,433
A long time ago.

28
00:02:25,186 --> 00:02:26,354
-Thank you.
-Thank you.

29
00:02:26,437 --> 00:02:30,066
CSI SCIENTIFIC INVESTIGATIONS
FIELD TRAINING

30
00:02:33,528 --> 00:02:36,281
3 MISSED CALLS
DETECTIVE NAM IL-YOUNG

31
00:02:40,160 --> 00:02:41,744
Detective Nam, you called me.

32
00:02:41,828 --> 00:02:44,289
<i>-Chief Kook.</i>
-I had a lecture at the Police University.

33
00:02:44,372 --> 00:02:45,331
I saw it just now.

34
00:02:45,415 --> 00:02:46,332
It's a robbery case.

35
00:02:46,416 --> 00:02:49,294
They found it suspicious,
so Captain Yoon and I took a look.

36
00:02:49,377 --> 00:02:53,256
It reminded me of timid aggression
and I think there's something.

37
00:02:53,339 --> 00:02:55,133
YEONGDEUNGPO POLICE STATION

38
00:02:55,216 --> 00:02:58,011
<i>I told Inspector Song right away,
and we rushed here together.</i>

39
00:02:58,595 --> 00:03:00,096
<i>Yeongdeungpo Police Station.</i>

40
00:03:00,638 --> 00:03:03,224
-Good day.
<i>-He went to get a confession out of him.</i>

41
00:03:04,100 --> 00:03:06,811
You were convicted of theft
and rape in the past.

42
00:03:06,895 --> 00:03:08,521
You were in jail for quite a while.

43
00:03:08,605 --> 00:03:10,565
I got caught by some unlucky chance.

44
00:03:11,357 --> 00:03:12,650
I didn't even get to do what I intended.

45
00:03:15,987 --> 00:03:17,155
By some unlucky chance?

46
00:03:17,238 --> 00:03:19,073
Had I been lucky,
I wouldn't have been caught.

47
00:03:21,576 --> 00:03:23,912
You broke into the villa
in Sinheung-dong to steal money, right?

48
00:03:24,495 --> 00:03:25,413
Yes.

49
00:03:27,415 --> 00:03:29,292
But you only managed to steal 10,000 won.

50
00:03:30,293 --> 00:03:32,378
-Once again, you were unlucky.
-Exactly.

51
00:03:33,338 --> 00:03:35,089
Who knew they'd be so poor?

52
00:03:36,466 --> 00:03:38,092
Why didn't you steal any valuables?

53
00:03:38,176 --> 00:03:41,596
Stealing stuff like that
could leave a trace.

54
00:03:42,889 --> 00:03:44,557
I only steal cash.

55
00:03:46,517 --> 00:03:48,102
You're very cautious.

56
00:03:50,188 --> 00:03:51,105
Yes, I am.

57
00:03:54,192 --> 00:03:56,402
I'm very thorough
when it comes to these things.

58
00:03:59,447 --> 00:04:02,283
-Like Gu Young-chun?
-He's a bluffer.

59
00:04:02,367 --> 00:04:03,826
How do you know?

60
00:04:03,910 --> 00:04:05,453
I could tell right away.

61
00:04:07,247 --> 00:04:09,290
You're right. I met him.

62
00:04:09,374 --> 00:04:12,502
He indeed is a bluffer and a loser.

63
00:04:12,585 --> 00:04:15,171
How many people did he say he killed?

64
00:04:15,255 --> 00:04:16,506
Why do you ask?

65
00:04:16,589 --> 00:04:20,009
I think he's lying
when he didn't even kill that many.

66
00:04:21,636 --> 00:04:23,263
He said he killed all those people.

67
00:04:24,138 --> 00:04:26,516
I know. You're right.

68
00:04:27,350 --> 00:04:28,601
The Imyeong-dong murder.

69
00:04:30,019 --> 00:04:31,521
That wasn't him, either.

70
00:04:38,152 --> 00:04:40,571
You're a good judge of character.
You've never even met him.

71
00:04:41,489 --> 00:04:43,032
I know these things.

72
00:04:43,116 --> 00:04:44,242
But I have to say,

73
00:04:45,243 --> 00:04:47,203
I've never seen a robber
with a pipe wrench.

74
00:04:47,287 --> 00:04:48,579
Why did you pick such a heavy tool?

75
00:04:48,663 --> 00:04:50,373
Because I may have to kill them.

76
00:04:50,456 --> 00:04:51,958
Why do you have to kill them?

77
00:04:52,041 --> 00:04:54,961
Goodness. Because they saw me.

78
00:04:55,628 --> 00:04:56,879
Are you really a detective?

79
00:04:58,423 --> 00:05:00,633
But most robbers use knives. Am I wrong?

80
00:05:00,717 --> 00:05:02,927
When you stab someone,
they don't always die.

81
00:05:03,511 --> 00:05:05,388
-How do you know?
-Well…

82
00:05:07,890 --> 00:05:08,850
That's…

83
00:05:10,143 --> 00:05:11,686
You know everything.

84
00:05:12,270 --> 00:05:15,023
I know a thing or two
when it comes to this stuff.

85
00:05:17,150 --> 00:05:19,652
But there are more affluent neighborhoods.

86
00:05:19,736 --> 00:05:21,195
Why Sinheung-dong of all places?

87
00:05:21,279 --> 00:05:23,531
Many rich people live in Gangnam.

88
00:05:24,574 --> 00:05:26,701
So I was going to pick my targets there,

89
00:05:27,744 --> 00:05:30,038
but I couldn't
because security was so tight.

90
00:05:31,039 --> 00:05:34,167
So you changed your plan
and targeted low-income buildings.

91
00:05:34,250 --> 00:05:37,503
Poor people can't afford to worry
about security, so they had no choice.

92
00:05:39,005 --> 00:05:40,798
Don't you feel bad for them?

93
00:05:40,882 --> 00:05:42,050
Why should I?

94
00:05:44,844 --> 00:05:46,721
It's their fault for being poor.

95
00:05:55,688 --> 00:05:57,523
-Then why did you start the fire?
-What?

96
00:05:58,608 --> 00:05:59,609
I…

97
00:06:00,443 --> 00:06:01,986
That wasn't me.

98
00:06:03,154 --> 00:06:04,155
I didn't do it.

99
00:06:05,198 --> 00:06:06,657
I didn't start the fire.

100
00:06:06,741 --> 00:06:09,243
I didn't start the fire.

101
00:06:15,083 --> 00:06:17,168
All right,
we can talk about that again later.

102
00:06:18,002 --> 00:06:21,089
Being with strangers in jail
must not have been easy.

103
00:06:21,839 --> 00:06:23,132
I know what it's like.

104
00:06:24,842 --> 00:06:25,802
How do you know?

105
00:06:25,885 --> 00:06:27,970
I'm an introvert too, just like you.

106
00:06:29,097 --> 00:06:30,598
When I'm keeping to myself,

107
00:06:30,681 --> 00:06:32,475
people assume I don't know anything.

108
00:06:33,142 --> 00:06:34,393
They all look down on me.

109
00:06:39,649 --> 00:06:40,566
Totally.

110
00:06:43,444 --> 00:06:45,279
Everyone thinks I'm an idiot!

111
00:06:49,659 --> 00:06:53,579
The detectives here won't hit you.
And no one here thinks you're an idiot.

112
00:06:54,580 --> 00:06:56,207
Everyone here

113
00:06:56,290 --> 00:06:58,835
understands you.

114
00:06:59,418 --> 00:07:00,294
Everyone…

115
00:07:03,256 --> 00:07:04,715
hated me.

116
00:07:05,466 --> 00:07:07,009
Everywhere I went,

117
00:07:07,552 --> 00:07:09,095
I had to suffer and get beaten up.

118
00:07:11,180 --> 00:07:12,723
I even had to put up
with that awful thing.

119
00:07:14,559 --> 00:07:15,935
When?

120
00:07:16,018 --> 00:07:18,771
-When I was little.
-How old were you?

121
00:07:18,855 --> 00:07:20,189
When I was in elementary school.

122
00:07:23,943 --> 00:07:24,986
Who did that to you?

123
00:07:26,529 --> 00:07:28,030
An old man in my neighborhood.

124
00:07:31,033 --> 00:07:32,618
That must've been a lot to handle.

125
00:07:34,245 --> 00:07:35,872
Do you want to keep talking to me?

126
00:07:37,748 --> 00:07:38,791
Yes.

127
00:07:42,253 --> 00:07:45,715
Then answer every question
the detectives here ask you.

128
00:07:47,258 --> 00:07:48,718
Do that, and we'll talk again.

129
00:07:49,302 --> 00:07:51,012
I don't want to go back to jail.

130
00:07:51,929 --> 00:07:56,100
Whenever I think about that time,
I'm upset and furious to death.

131
00:07:57,894 --> 00:08:00,897
If you suffered that much,
why didn't you speak with the guards?

132
00:08:02,023 --> 00:08:03,566
I complained numerous times,

133
00:08:04,942 --> 00:08:06,652
but no one listened.

134
00:08:10,573 --> 00:08:11,782
I…

135
00:08:16,662 --> 00:08:19,165
The people here will listen
to everything you say,

136
00:08:20,333 --> 00:08:22,043
so don't worry and just tell them.

137
00:08:28,758 --> 00:08:30,259
And then what?

138
00:08:33,513 --> 00:08:35,431
What will happen
if I tell them everything?

139
00:08:38,684 --> 00:08:40,394
What do you think will happen
if you don't?

140
00:08:42,688 --> 00:08:44,357
I'm sure you don't want

141
00:08:45,650 --> 00:08:47,401
to relive the misery you experienced.

142
00:08:49,654 --> 00:08:51,948
I'll tell them everything I did.

143
00:08:53,199 --> 00:08:54,325
Get me a single cell.

144
00:08:55,201 --> 00:08:56,953
A single cell. That's all I ask for.

145
00:08:58,204 --> 00:08:59,247
Mr. Nam Ki-Tae.

146
00:09:01,374 --> 00:09:04,710
The detectives here know
all about the Imyeong-dong case

147
00:09:05,878 --> 00:09:07,964
as well as the Mogu-dong arson case.

148
00:09:09,257 --> 00:09:11,050
So I suggest you confess voluntarily.

149
00:09:12,593 --> 00:09:13,594
Okay.

150
00:09:20,226 --> 00:09:22,436
Let me know if you need anything.

151
00:09:22,520 --> 00:09:23,813
I'll help you.

152
00:09:34,782 --> 00:09:38,536
If you're willing to open up and confess,
the detectives here will be all ears.

153
00:09:39,787 --> 00:09:41,289
Everyone here

154
00:09:41,872 --> 00:09:44,375
wants to hear you out, just like I do.

155
00:09:45,334 --> 00:09:46,460
But the thing is,

156
00:09:48,796 --> 00:09:50,756
I don't remember every single thing I did.

157
00:09:51,841 --> 00:09:54,093
I just walked around and did it
whenever I felt like it.

158
00:09:54,176 --> 00:09:56,971
So I don't think I can recall
where each one took place.

159
00:09:59,557 --> 00:10:00,933
That's okay.

160
00:10:01,017 --> 00:10:02,560
Just tell us what you remember.

161
00:10:02,643 --> 00:10:04,186
You can take your time.

162
00:10:04,979 --> 00:10:06,063
I will be…

163
00:10:09,525 --> 00:10:11,193
sentenced to death anyway, won't I?

164
00:10:15,865 --> 00:10:17,241
Don't think like that.

165
00:10:18,242 --> 00:10:20,036
We have to talk again, you know?

166
00:10:27,752 --> 00:10:28,961
All right, then.

167
00:10:40,598 --> 00:10:43,809
INTERROGATION ROOM

168
00:10:56,113 --> 00:10:57,156
You're here.

169
00:10:57,907 --> 00:10:59,033
Yes.

170
00:11:02,328 --> 00:11:04,121
-He's here.
-Hello, sir.

171
00:11:05,081 --> 00:11:06,457
How did it go?

172
00:11:06,540 --> 00:11:08,876
-Can we go in now?
-No, wait.

173
00:11:10,378 --> 00:11:13,714
The Southwest Case. It was Nam Ki-Tae.

174
00:11:13,798 --> 00:11:16,133
-See?
-I told you.

175
00:11:16,217 --> 00:11:17,760
The Imyeong-dong case too.

176
00:11:18,427 --> 00:11:19,929
-That was also him.
-What?

177
00:11:20,012 --> 00:11:21,222
-Goodness.
-Unbelievable.

178
00:11:21,305 --> 00:11:22,640
Did he confess?

179
00:11:22,723 --> 00:11:23,891
Yes.

180
00:11:23,974 --> 00:11:26,644
Gosh, we went through so much
because of that case.

181
00:11:26,727 --> 00:11:29,105
We should be strategic
about interrogating him.

182
00:11:29,188 --> 00:11:30,314
Okay.

183
00:11:30,856 --> 00:11:32,733
He's emotionally unstable.

184
00:11:32,817 --> 00:11:35,903
And he seems socially inept.
He struggles to communicate with others.

185
00:11:35,986 --> 00:11:38,280
I knew it.
I thought he looked like a dimwit.

186
00:11:38,364 --> 00:11:41,742
He's never had a relationship with anyone
who supports his words and actions.

187
00:11:42,326 --> 00:11:44,662
Then how should we go about
interrogating him?

188
00:11:44,745 --> 00:11:46,038
If we get angry or yell,

189
00:11:46,122 --> 00:11:47,790
he won't want to talk.

190
00:11:47,873 --> 00:11:49,208
We have to humor him too?

191
00:11:49,291 --> 00:11:51,460
I'm not asking you
to praise him for his crimes.

192
00:11:51,544 --> 00:11:55,131
These suspects already know
what the detectives are after.

193
00:11:55,214 --> 00:11:57,425
Even if you treat them nicely,
they won't trust you.

194
00:11:57,508 --> 00:12:00,678
She's right. If you seem
to overly approve of what they did,

195
00:12:00,761 --> 00:12:02,513
it can actually backfire.

196
00:12:02,596 --> 00:12:03,597
Then what do we do?

197
00:12:03,681 --> 00:12:05,474
Try to avoid showing him
any kind of judgment,

198
00:12:05,558 --> 00:12:07,309
be it positive or negative.

199
00:12:07,393 --> 00:12:09,520
Try to let him do the talking.

200
00:12:09,603 --> 00:12:11,897
Nam Ki-tae has a high tendency
to be socially withdrawn.

201
00:12:11,981 --> 00:12:15,025
He'll become anxious if there are
too many detectives around him.

202
00:12:15,109 --> 00:12:17,653
So we'll have only
a minimal number of people in there.

203
00:12:17,736 --> 00:12:21,157
Why are there so many rules
over a simple interrogation?

204
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:22,324
There has to be.

205
00:12:23,409 --> 00:12:25,244
As everyone here knows,

206
00:12:25,327 --> 00:12:27,788
Nam Ki-Tae is unlike
any other violent criminal.

207
00:12:27,872 --> 00:12:29,915
The victims of the Southwest Case

208
00:12:29,999 --> 00:12:32,710
that we are aware of
come to a total of 14.

209
00:12:32,793 --> 00:12:35,296
Among them, six died.

210
00:12:35,379 --> 00:12:37,840
And there is a high possibility
of many more victims.

211
00:12:37,923 --> 00:12:41,302
This means we cannot miss
even one innocent victim.

212
00:12:41,385 --> 00:12:44,597
That is how we can be responsible
in this current situation.

213
00:12:44,680 --> 00:12:47,183
Also, you should not throw
random questions at him.

214
00:12:47,266 --> 00:12:49,185
He has poor communication skills,
so if he gets confused,

215
00:12:49,268 --> 00:12:50,853
he might blurt out just anything.

216
00:12:50,936 --> 00:12:54,023
From now on, we should write down
our questions beforehand.

217
00:12:54,106 --> 00:12:55,149
That is a good idea.

218
00:12:55,858 --> 00:12:58,694
If you don't, he might even agree
with the wrong parts

219
00:12:59,653 --> 00:13:01,197
and give up on making a statement.

220
00:13:02,656 --> 00:13:03,866
And one more thing.

221
00:13:05,367 --> 00:13:06,869
Until the interrogation is over,

222
00:13:06,952 --> 00:13:10,122
pick out one detective who'll converse
with him the most efficiently.

223
00:13:10,873 --> 00:13:13,584
It'll be the most effective
in getting the answer you want.

224
00:13:14,126 --> 00:13:16,003
SEOUL METROPOLITAN POLICE AGENCY

225
00:13:25,554 --> 00:13:26,514
Nam Ki-Tae was

226
00:13:27,264 --> 00:13:30,559
-raped in his childhood.
-By whom?

227
00:13:30,643 --> 00:13:32,144
He just said
an elderly person in his town.

228
00:13:32,228 --> 00:13:34,688
Around when in his childhood?

229
00:13:34,772 --> 00:13:36,106
In elementary school.

230
00:13:36,190 --> 00:13:40,110
He didn't want to elaborate,
so I didn't press him.

231
00:13:40,694 --> 00:13:43,155
Nam Ki-Tae was charged with rape
a few times, right?

232
00:13:43,239 --> 00:13:45,866
From child rape to adults, at every age.

233
00:13:45,950 --> 00:13:47,910
There is no crime he stayed away from.

234
00:13:47,993 --> 00:13:50,955
So how did you get him to confess
to the Imyeong-dong case?

235
00:13:51,038 --> 00:13:52,790
He was conscious of Gu Young-chun.

236
00:13:52,873 --> 00:13:55,793
He said Gu Young-chun was showing off
with something he did.

237
00:13:55,876 --> 00:13:57,169
So I provoked him and asked.

238
00:13:58,045 --> 00:13:59,296
Unbelievable.

239
00:13:59,380 --> 00:14:01,840
Were they competitive or something?

240
00:14:03,008 --> 00:14:04,009
Let's go inside.

241
00:14:05,803 --> 00:14:07,346
You walked around?

242
00:14:07,429 --> 00:14:10,099
Once I got off the subway,
I always walked from there.

243
00:14:11,517 --> 00:14:14,144
It's a pretty long journey
to the villa in Sinheung 6-dong.

244
00:14:14,228 --> 00:14:15,771
I'm really fit.

245
00:14:16,272 --> 00:14:18,190
I ran ten laps a day.

246
00:14:18,274 --> 00:14:19,400
Ten laps a day?

247
00:14:20,359 --> 00:14:21,861
I had to run fast to avoid getting caught.

248
00:14:22,444 --> 00:14:24,238
How did you choose your crime sites?

249
00:14:25,739 --> 00:14:27,533
I didn't choose anything in particular.

250
00:14:28,492 --> 00:14:30,536
I just walked in places with open doors.

251
00:14:30,619 --> 00:14:32,788
-Just blindly?
-Yes.

252
00:14:34,081 --> 00:14:36,876
People rarely lock
their balconies and windows.

253
00:14:36,959 --> 00:14:37,918
<i>Breaking news.</i>

254
00:14:38,002 --> 00:14:40,212
<i>A leading suspect
who terrorized the residents</i>

255
00:14:40,296 --> 00:14:42,590
<i>of the southwestern area of Seoul
in 2004 was caught.</i>

256
00:14:42,673 --> 00:14:45,259
{\an8}<i>Last night, he broke into Im's house
in Sinheung 6-dong,</i>

257
00:14:45,342 --> 00:14:46,802
<i>in an attempt to steal money.</i>

258
00:14:46,886 --> 00:14:48,721
<i>But after a fight with Im's father,
